Got it—here’s a clean, no-slang checklist to make writing read more naturally human while still staying formal and clear:

✅ 1. Vary Sentence Structure
Mix short, medium, and long sentences

Avoid repeating the same pattern (e.g., always starting with “This shows…”)

Example:

Instead of: “This shows… This also shows… This proves…”

Use: “This suggests… Additionally… A further implication is…”

✅ 2. Add Specificity
Include precise details, examples, or context

AI writing is often general; human writing is more grounded

Example:

Weak: “Many people were affected.”

Strong: “Thousands of factory workers in northern cities lost their jobs.”

✅ 3. Use Natural Imperfection
Slightly vary tone or phrasing

It is acceptable to have minor asymmetry in sentence flow

(Not errors—just less mechanical uniformity)

✅ 4. Avoid Overly Perfect Transitions
Do not overuse connectors like:

“Furthermore”

“Moreover”

“In conclusion” (especially repeatedly)

Use them selectively, not every paragraph

✅ 5. Show Reasoning, Not Just Conclusions
Humans often explain how they reached a point, not just the result

Example:

Basic: “This was important.”

Better: “This was important because it shifted public opinion and influenced policy decisions.”

✅ 6. Vary Vocabulary Naturally
Avoid repeating the same key words too often

Use synonyms where appropriate, but do not force them

✅ 7. Include Subtle Personal Framing (if allowed)
Phrases like:

“This suggests that…”

“It can be argued that…”

“One possible explanation is…”

These reflect human interpretation rather than robotic certainty

✅ 8. Break Perfect Paragraph Symmetry
AI often writes paragraphs that are nearly identical in length and structure

Let some be shorter or more detailed than others

✅ 9. Use Concrete Examples
Support points with real or hypothetical examples

This adds depth and reduces the “generic” feel

✅ 10. Read It Aloud
If it sounds too smooth or uniform, revise

Human writing usually has slight rhythm variation

⚠️ Final Note
The goal is not to “trick” detection systems, but to produce writing that reflects authentic thinking, variation, and clarity—qualities associated with human authorship.

